<HEADLINE>
<P>
AQMD RULING IN TOXICS RELEASE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * Re "AQMD Adopts Scaled-Back Pollution Rule," April 9: 
</P>
<P>
 In assessing the costs of environmental legislation, or for that matter any 
legislation that seeks to affect societal behavior, it seems to be a common 
error to ignore the action-forcing intent that underlies them. It would "cost" 
industry $10 million, or whatever, a year to meet certain emission mandates, 
but the benefits to society are not limited to actual reductions in pollution 
over the same time period as the economic expense.Ecological processes often 
work to their own time scale. But even more than this, there is another benefit 
which accrues to society. And that is innovation. 
</P>
<P>
 This points to another common error, that of blurring the distinction between 
technology and ingenuity. Technological solutions are bounded by scientific 
knowledge and by the economics of production. Human ingenuity is what, 
historically, has enabled us to push the boundaries of what is doable in the 
moment. It is when what needs doing, whether by choice or fiat, becomes 
undoable, that innovation happens. 
</P>
<P>
 I suspect that behind every worthwhile or good thing that has emerged from 
human society, somewhere in our past there lies a mandate. Norms do not 
magically appear. They emerge from the principles and rules of organizations 
and institutions. 
</P>
<P>
 ASHWANI VASISHTH 
</P>
<P>
 Los Angeles 
</P>
<P>
 * It is hard to believe that the AQMD and Los Angeles business can be so 
uncaring about the people they kill. To feel that it doesn't matter -- there 
will always be plenty to take their places -- is medieval, perhaps barbaric. 
This is the attitude we ascribe to the young kids running rampant on our 
streets these days. 
</P>
<P>
 I'm happy to be leaving Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
 LOUISE O. STAFFORD 
</P>
<P>
 Northridge 
</P>
