<P>
 The Securities and Exchange Commission voted to require investment advisers 
that run "wrap-fee" programs to provide better information on the cost of the 
accounts and how they are managed.Wrap-fee programs sponsored by brokerage 
firms combine asset-management and transaction costs in one flat fee, typically 
about 3% a year, based on a percentage of assets under management. By Oct. 1, 
brokerage firms will have to give investors separate brochures when they open 
wrap-fee accounts. Currently, an investor opening such an account receives a 
thick disclosure statement called Form ADV, which is like a prospectus on the 
investment adviser. 
