<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: REAL ESTATE; NON-JAPANESE ASIAN INVESTORS ENTERING THE HOUSING 
MARKET 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by Debora Vrana, Times special correspondent 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 After being badly burned in the real estate downturn, many Japanese investors 
are pulling out of the U.S. real estate market. But in Orange County, at least, 
other Asian investors are entering the market, investing mostly in housing 
projects, according to Mike Meyer, managing partner of the Newport Beach office 
of Kenneth Leventhal & Co., the accounting firm.In 1990, Japanese companies had 
invested about $656 million in Orange County. There were no new investments in 
1992, however, and nothing last year either. 
</P>
<P>
 But now investors from Taiwan, South Korea and other parts of Asia are showing 
up. A wealthy Hong Kong investor is actively purchasing residential housing 
lots in the county, Meyer said. 
</P>
<P>
 "We have met with some of these other Asian investors, and they are seeking 
mainly joint venture opportunities in residential projects in Orange County and 
the Inland Empire," Meyer said.  
</P>
<P>
 Orange County will see more non-Japanese Asian real estate investors, he said. 
They "are anxious to purchase residential lots at the bottom of the cycle and 
watch the value increase as the local housing market improves." 
</P>
<P>
 Kenneth Leventhal released a study this week showing that the Japanese are 
trying to sell or lower their debt in U.S. real estate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
