VENTURA COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kenneth R. Weiss 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 ANOTHER SHAKE: The Marmonte League has decided to give sportsmanship another 
chance. Reversing an earlier decision, high school principals from Camarillo to 
Thousand Oaks have lifted a ban on the traditional post-game handshake (A1). 
The schools sacked the symbol of fair play after it prompted a fistfight. But 
the no-handshake rule sparked an even greater commotion, gaining nationwide 
attention. Sports Illustrated cited the handshake ban as a sign that the 
apocalypse is nigh. 
</P>
<P>
 FRONT-RUNNERS: The Field Poll shows state Sen. Cathie Wright of Simi Valley 
and former Assemblyman Tom McClintock of Thousand Oaks as the leading 
Republicans in two statewide races . . . . Wright has the support of 23% of 
Republicans for the GOP nomination for lieutenant governor. McClintock has 23% 
of GOP support for state controller. But 64% remain undecided in Wright's race 
and 59% in McClintock's. "When more than 50% of the voters haven't decided," 
says the poll's director, "it's really a tossup." 
</P>
<P>
 HOLY CHUTZPAH: The Simi Valley priest who beat two embezzlement charges is 
accusing the Catholic Archdiocese in Los Angeles of acting "immorally and 
unethically in actively supporting the criminal prosecution against me." (B1). 
. . Father David Dean Piroli said the church accused him of stealing money that 
it was not sure it was missing and suppressed evidence that would have helped 
his defense. Standing before TV cameras, he said: "No one, not even the Holy 
Father himself, should put himself or herself above the law." 
</P>
<P>
 WHAT A GEM: Jewel Pedi is stepping down from her position as executive 
director of Food Share, the hugely successful food bank in Oxnard. Jewel was 
there from the beginning in 1978, when a band of volunteers ran Food Share out 
of a two-car garage. Now, she directs the organization that feeds 127,000 
people a month through a wide network of relief agencies. Food Share's Dee Volz 
considers Pedi a CEO with a heart: "She has a strong combination of efficiency 
and caring." 
</P>
